    <title>Polluting the head section for the sake of adding 3rd party services</title>
    <link href="https://jmperezperez.com//head-section-meta-tags-hell"/>
    <id>https://jmperezperez.com//head-section-meta-tags-hell</id>
    <published>2013-04-04T13:09:47.000Z</published>
    <updated>2018-12-16T17:51:46.000Z</updated>
    
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p><img src="/assets/images/posts/head-meta-tags.png" alt="Meta tags hell">
The head section of a page is becoming the place to include information for integrating your page with external services. Thus, if you want to include support for <a href="http://developers.facebook.com/docs/opengraphprotocol/">Facebook’s Open Graph Protocol</a> or <a href="https://dev.twitter.com/docs/cards">Twitter Cards</a>, you need to include some custom meta tags inside the head section. This also applies to iOS large app icons or Microsoft shortcut integration.</p>
<span id="more"></span>
<p>Have a look at a page such as <a href="http://www.theverge.com/2013/4/3/4179236/the-facebook-phone-is-coming-and-its-already-in-your-pocket/">this news on The Verge</a> and view its source HTML code. Removing common meta tags such as content type, favicon, RSS or description, we have this:</p>
